{"author":"RebarBotNava","data":{"fields":{"description":"## Why\n`test_code_review_ws5.py::test_security_rule_yaml_files_are_present_and_nonempty` (`:36-39`)\nonly checks one file is non-empty and greps another for the substrings `rebar.builtin.security.`\nand `rules:`. Invalid YAML, duplicate ids, malformed rule objects, wrong severities, or an\nunusable pattern all satisfy it. VALIDATED.\n\n## Definitions (make the ACs concrete)\n- **Rule family** = one vendored security-rule YAML file under\n  `src/rebar/grounding/detectors/builtin/`. There are three security families:\n  `security_iac_public_exposure.yaml`, `security_owasp_cwe.yaml`,\n  `security_secrets_gitleaks.yaml`.\n- **Loaded via the production loader** = through `rebar.grounding.detectors.registry`\n  (`load_registry` / the file-level `_detectors_from_file`), which returns `Detector`\n  objects (id, backend, namespace, envelope, rule) — NOT hand-parsed YAML.\n- **Fails closed (observable)** = when a family file is malformed (invalid YAML, or a rule\n  missing its required `id`), the production loader yields ZERO detectors FROM THAT FILE and\n  records the loss (an entry in `Registry.parse_drops`, or the specific rule dropped) — the\n  loss is SURFACED, never silently masked as a working registry that omits the rule. The test\n  asserts both the absence of the detector and the recorded drop.\n\n## What\nReplace the substring/presence assertions with loader-based behavioral checks. Two production\nloader seams are used (both are the real code `load_registry` runs — no hand-parsing):\n`load_registry()` (loads the real built-in dir) for the POSITIVE assertions, and the file-level\n`registry._detectors_from_file(path) -> (detectors, reason)` for the FAIL-CLOSED case against a\ntemp malformed file (`load_registry` hardcodes `_builtin_dir()`, so a temp dir is fed to the\nfile-level loader instead).\n\n1. Positive: call `load_registry()` and, for each of the three security families, assert the\n   EXACT set of detector ids contributed by that family, their `backend`, and their declared\n   severity (from the rule/envelope metadata) — pinning the real loaded contract, not a\n   substring. (Match detectors to a family by their `source_path` / id namespace.)\n2. Fail-closed (observable loss, never a silent working detector), via\n   `_detectors_from_file(temp_path)`:\n   - **Broken YAML:** a temp file with invalid YAML returns `([], \"parse_error\")` — ZERO\n     detectors AND a non-None reason (the drop is surfaced, per the loader's documented\n     fail-open-with-reason contract), so a downstream pin/expected-id check would catch it.\n   - **Rule with no `id`:** a temp file that copies a family but REMOVES one rule's `id`\n     yields detectors for the file's OTHER (well-formed) rules but NOT for the id-less one —\n     rule-level fail-closed: `_detector_from_rule` never manufactures a detector from a rule\n     lacking a usable id. (Assert the id-less rule's would-be detector is absent while its\n     siblings load.)\n3. Keep a fast presence/freshness guard ONLY if explicitly labeled as such (not the coverage\n   claim).\n\nNote: matcher EXECUTION (running opengrep/ast-grep against positive/negative code snippets)\nis NOT asserted here because it requires the external backend binary, which is not guaranteed\nin unit CI; this ticket pins the loaded rule CONTRACT (ids/backends/severities) and the\nfail-closed loader behavior, which are the untested gaps. (Matcher execution is exercised\nelsewhere where the backend is available.)\n\n## Scope\n- `tests/unit/test_code_review_ws5.py` — loader-based id/backend/severity assertions + the\n  fail-closed malformed-data test.\n- `src/rebar/grounding/detectors/builtin/` — reference only (validated, not modified).\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n- [ ] For each of the three security families, the test loads it via the production\n      `load_registry` and asserts the exact detector ids, their backends, and their severities.\n- [ ] A fail-closed test feeds malformed vendored data through `_detectors_from_file`: broken\n      YAML yields `([], \"parse_error\")` (zero detectors + recorded reason); a rule with no `id`\n      is absent while the file's well-formed sibling rules still load — not silently loaded.\n- [ ] The old substring/presence-only assertion is removed (or explicitly relabeled as a fast\n      freshness guard, distinct from the coverage claim).\n- [ ] `make test` green."}},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"EDIT","timestamp":1783804848614444001,"uuid":"06e67acb-2adc-4167-b706-b469694fdf52"}